The US's Anti-China Tech War
From New York — The worst foreign policy decision made by the previous generation (and even earlier generations) of Americans was the 2003 "war of choice" against Iraq, which claimed as its purpose the elimination — although they did not actually exist — of weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity of understanding the flawed logic behind this catastrophic decision has become unprecedentedly significant, as the same logic is now being used to justify similar misleading US policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists was small (for example, 1%), we should act as if it were certain to happen.
But this line of reasoning almost always leads to erroneous decisions.
However, the United States and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack China's technology.
According to the U.S. government, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should respond by treating it as certainly harmful and banning it.
Correct decision-making would apply probability estimates to various alternative courses of action.
A generation ago, U.S. policymakers should not only have considered the (alleged) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of launching a war based on multiple flawed premises.
By focusing solely on that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) distracted the public from the fact that the Iraq War actually lacked legitimacy and would severely undermine the stability of the Middle East and global politics.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not only that it compels action based on minimal risks without considering the high potential costs, but also that politicians always stoke fear for some ulterior motives.
This is exactly what U.S. leaders are doing again: stirring panic about Chinese technology companies by pointing out and exaggerating certain minor risks.
The most relevant (but not the only) example of this is the U.S. government's attack on the communications technology company Huawei.
The U.S. is gradually closing its domestic market to the company and striving to eliminate its global business.
Just like with Iraq, the U.S. may ultimately cause an unwarranted geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been closely following Huawei's technological advancements because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide significant momentum for poverty alleviation and the achievement of other United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and have encouraged the industry to enhance its actions in support of the Sustainable Development Goals.
I wrote a brief foreword (unpaid) for a report by Huawei on this topic, and as a result, I was criticized by those hostile to China. I then asked industry leaders and government officials if there was any evidence that Huawei had engaged in any inappropriate behavior, and the repeated answer was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trusted industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the US government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment may pose a threat to global security.
US officials claim that "backdoors" in Huawei's software or hardware could allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance worldwide.
They point out that China's legal requirements compel Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But now the facts are clear.
Huawei's 5G equipment is low-cost and high-quality, currently leading many competitors and has already begun to roll out.
Its high performance stems from massive investments in R&D over the years, economies of scale, and its extensive experience in China's digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology for sustainable development, it would be clearly unwise for low-income economies around the world to reject the early deployment of 5G.
However, despite the lack of any evidence of backdoors, the United States is still lobbying the world to distance itself from Huawei.
The United States' argument is generalizable.
As one U.S. Federal Communications Commissioner stated: "The country that has 5G will have the related innovations and set the standards for the rest of the world, and that country is currently unlikely to be the United States."
Other countries — especially the United Kingdom — have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software and hardware.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they can almost certainly be closed at that time.
The debate over Huawei is also intense in Germany, as the US government threatens to cut intelligence cooperation unless authorities keep Huawei's 5G technology out.
Perhaps under pressure from the US, the head of Germany's federal intelligence agency recently made a statement resembling Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a domain suitable for groups that cannot be fully trusted."
Yet he was unable to provide any concrete evidence of specific wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel has been fighting behind the scenes to keep the market open for Huawei.
But ironically, the US's complaints partly reflect its own surveillance activities at home and abroad — although this is no longer news.
Chinese equipment might make it more difficult for the US government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any unjustified surveillance by any government should be stopped.
Independent monitoring by the United Nations to reduce such activities should be part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards rather than fighting a technological war.
The threatening impact of the US demand to ban Huawei is not limited to the early rollout of 5G networks, but also poses significant risks to the rules-based trading system.
The United States is no longer the uncontested global leader in technology, and President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete within a rules-based system.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
They also attempt to undermine the World Trade Organization by paralyzing its dispute resolution mechanism, which also reflects their attitude toward the model of global rules.
If the Trump administration succeeds in dividing the world into different technological blocs, the risk of future conflicts will multiply.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade, which not only improved global efficiency and expanded the U.S. technology market, but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
And part of the collapse was due to the protectionist tariffs imposed by the United States under the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act of 1930, which exacerbated the Great Depression, leading to the rise of Hitler, and ultimately contributed to the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other areas, in the realm of international affairs, stoking fear and acting on it — rather than acting on evidence — is a path to destruction.
Let us stick to rationality, evidence, and rules, which is the safest approach.
Let us establish independent monitoring bodies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to spy on other countries or launch cyber warfare.
This way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
